1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:08,343
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samasambuddhasah.

2
00:00:09,226 --> 00:00:17,719
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samasambuddhasah.

3
00:00:18,155 --> 00:00:31,251
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodassam Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

4
00:00:32,914 --> 00:00:47,554
So, just to carry on with these parami, the next one is Satcha S-A-C-C-A The C in Pali is always Ch and it translates as honesty, truthfulness.

5
00:00:47,786 --> 00:00:52,034
And I think we can pass over, you know, telling the great whoppers.

6
00:00:52,054 --> 00:00:53,777
I think we've gone beyond that.

7
00:00:54,759 --> 00:00:56,664
But Churchill talked about it.

8
00:00:56,844 --> 00:01:00,851
Churchill put it as being economical with the truth.

9
00:01:02,283 --> 00:01:06,950
But the other dishonesty is to do with exaggeration.

10
00:01:07,971 --> 00:01:12,278
And we tend to exaggerate in order to impress people.

11
00:01:12,558 --> 00:01:15,382
It's to do with the three conceits.

12
00:01:15,582 --> 00:01:20,409
We're either trying to impress somebody that we're better than we are, or worse than we are,

13
00:01:20,390 --> 00:01:23,394
or we're equal to them, even though we know we're not.

14
00:01:24,115 --> 00:01:46,971
So that sort of exaggeration that we put about ourselves, there's also exaggeration about the weather, the climate change, the financial crisis, just the way we talk about it, sort of exaggerating it to create some sort of impression.

15
00:01:46,950 --> 00:01:55,546
And so long as, I think it's a case of just being aware of what we're saying and what we're doing.

16
00:01:55,606 --> 00:01:57,170
It's always to do with his right speech.

17
00:01:57,850 --> 00:02:06,626
But there's a point where I think exaggeration leaves, should we say, the humorous and moves into just that little area of slight untruth.

18
00:02:07,067 --> 00:02:09,211
You just have to be careful.

19
00:02:09,192 --> 00:02:14,016
I mean, I've often, I've occasionally found myself, when somebody's come up with a Pali word, pretending that I know it.

20
00:02:15,957 --> 00:02:16,658
It embarrasses me.

21
00:02:17,159 --> 00:02:20,182
And then I've got to go and look it up, you know.

22
00:02:20,203 --> 00:02:25,046
And it's just because I've got in my head that I know Pali words, and I don't.

23
00:02:25,527 --> 00:02:29,551
You know, I've got to get over the fact that I'm not a Pali scholar.

24
00:02:30,151 --> 00:02:38,439
And it's happened to me about, well, once I remember distinctly, you know, being corrected, and so I'm umbed and hard and made some sort of excuse about it.

25
00:02:40,006 --> 00:02:46,415
So these things, you know, they slip in and they're coming from that sense of self, basically.

26
00:02:46,436 --> 00:02:51,002
So just being aware of where we exaggerate is just slipping into untruth.

27
00:02:51,623 --> 00:03:02,039
In terms of meditation, it's a real, it can be a real problem because it was funny, when I used to work with my Eastern teachers, they were often all about honesty.

28
00:03:02,961 --> 00:03:03,802
And

29
00:03:03,951 --> 00:03:08,782
It was because Westerners would talk about their experience.

30
00:03:08,802 --> 00:03:20,228
And I never really found out whether it was the fact that Westerners were exaggerating or whether it was the teachers who didn't believe that Westerners could attain these sort of experiences.

31
00:03:20,247 --> 00:03:20,407
LAUGHTER

32
00:03:20,911 --> 00:03:35,911
And I remember once saying to Ajahn Sumedho, Lumpur now, Lumpur Sumedho, I said, they think we're sort of spiritual nerds, like we would think of Easterners at one time as being technological twits.

33
00:03:36,972 --> 00:03:44,222
And so there was never that confusion, but they were always on about honesty, being honest in your reporting.

34
00:03:44,763 --> 00:03:50,310
So...

35
00:03:53,158 --> 00:03:56,343
The next one that is of interest is white lies.

36
00:03:57,545 --> 00:03:59,308
These are all to do with intentions.

37
00:03:59,870 --> 00:04:13,733
What's your intention in not saying something that you ought to say, or in saying something that is not right, but for some good reason.

38
00:04:13,712 --> 00:04:19,562
I think in former times it was very difficult to tell somebody they were dying.

39
00:04:20,444 --> 00:04:26,413
You always had to pretend that they weren't actually dying, even though the person probably felt that they were dying.

40
00:04:26,915 --> 00:04:35,028
These days people are a bit more open about that, but it's a case of...

41
00:04:35,009 --> 00:04:40,303
I suppose, having a good reason for not saying the truth and being clear about it.

42
00:04:40,985 --> 00:04:47,545
But I remember once there was an old teacher of mine from primary school whom I met and he became headmaster of a local place.

43
00:04:48,968 --> 00:04:50,233
And

44
00:04:50,651 --> 00:04:56,817
The catering service decided to serve TVP, textured vegetable protein, instead of meat.

45
00:04:57,798 --> 00:04:58,759
And he didn't tell the staff.

46
00:05:00,100 --> 00:05:06,708
And then he asked the staff what it was like, and of course they said it was all right, good mince, very nice meat, and all that sort of stuff.

47
00:05:06,728 --> 00:05:07,788
And then he told them.

48
00:05:07,809 --> 00:05:14,175
And they were very upset, because they felt they'd been used as guinea pigs, you see.

49
00:05:14,454 --> 00:05:15,656
It was all right doing it to the kids.

50
00:05:16,898 --> 00:05:19,360
And it was funny, because...

51
00:05:20,216 --> 00:05:24,663
He told me with this sense of astonishment as to why they were so upset about it.

52
00:05:26,144 --> 00:05:36,077
And it was like he was, in other words, what he didn't realize was that in not telling them, he presumed that they would be prejudiced.

53
00:05:36,098 --> 00:05:46,110
So if he'd have told them that it was TBP, they'd have eaten it with that critical mind and said, well, you know, this isn't like meat, it doesn't have the same crunch, it doesn't have this, it doesn't have that.

54
00:05:46,130 --> 00:05:48,334
And he sort of was tricking them in a way.

55
00:05:49,107 --> 00:05:50,870
So he got a bit of flack for that.

56
00:05:50,930 --> 00:05:53,896
But it just shows you, you see, it was a good intention in a sense.

57
00:05:53,976 --> 00:06:02,795
But from his point of view, there was this lack of trust in the teachers that they wouldn't accept this TVP business.

58
00:06:06,708 --> 00:06:12,841
Now, the one that's usually talked about in the commentaries is keeping your word, actually.

59
00:06:13,221 --> 00:06:16,127
That's the one they usually go on about, keeping your word.

60
00:06:17,228 --> 00:06:25,846
And I think we often find when somebody asks us to do something, we can be a bit too quick with the yes, I'll do it.

61
00:06:25,826 --> 00:06:31,336
You know, instead of just holding a minute and saying, well, you know, I'll have to think about it, I'll have to look at my diary or something.

62
00:06:31,937 --> 00:06:35,463
And you find yourself saying yes and then kicking yourself for doing it.

63
00:06:36,064 --> 00:06:47,987
And then when it comes to the time to actually help them out, moving house or painting and decorating or something, suddenly you're feeling ill, you know, you phone up and say, can't come, you know, there's a...

64
00:06:47,966 --> 00:06:51,274
An elephant's just entered the house and I've got to deal with it, things like that.

65
00:06:51,596 --> 00:06:55,245
And to get out of this hole you've got yourself in.

66
00:06:56,007 --> 00:06:58,834
And then you do it and you're feeling rotten all the time for doing it.

67
00:06:59,194 --> 00:07:04,288
And all it took was this moment of, you know, just saying, you know, well, I'm not sure I can help or what, you know.

68
00:07:06,023 --> 00:07:08,685
There's a lovely incident of that in Sri Lanka.

69
00:07:10,187 --> 00:07:15,654
Easterners, because of loss of face, have it very difficult to say no.

70
00:07:15,675 --> 00:07:19,699
I came across this when I was in the Kooten.

71
00:07:19,740 --> 00:07:21,642
I was trying to keep the rule very strictly.

72
00:07:21,762 --> 00:07:23,004
It was very difficult to do that.

73
00:07:23,725 --> 00:07:27,389
And so I would ask the office to buy me something.

74
00:07:28,112 --> 00:07:32,781
I mean, I can't remember what the object was now, but let's say it was apples.

75
00:07:33,343 --> 00:07:36,228
So I would say to them, can you get me so many apples?

76
00:07:36,908 --> 00:07:41,156
They were in trust with my money, you see, that I had.

77
00:07:41,177 --> 00:07:43,502
They were my capia, the ones who make it allowable.

78
00:07:44,122 --> 00:07:46,947
Well, if they couldn't get apples, they came with a whole load of oranges.

79
00:07:47,704 --> 00:07:51,074
You know, they couldn't sort of come to me and say, there aren't any apples.

80
00:07:51,093 --> 00:07:52,658
They had to come with something else.

81
00:07:53,019 --> 00:07:55,305
But eventually I got fed up because I was wasting all my money.

82
00:07:55,826 --> 00:07:59,435
So whenever, you know, I had to give up on asking them to do something.

83
00:08:00,377 --> 00:08:05,064
And there was this Australian monk, now this is really, you're going to come up laughing.

84
00:08:05,524 --> 00:08:16,420
So he had turned up in Sri Lanka and he had invited this senior monk, he kept going on about this senior monk, to come to Thailand with him.

85
00:08:16,440 --> 00:08:18,463
And the senior monk, you see, couldn't say no.

86
00:08:19,466 --> 00:08:19,946
He can't say no.

87
00:08:21,007 --> 00:08:23,831
So he does this shake of the head business, you know.

88
00:08:24,552 --> 00:08:27,297
And he bought a ticket, bought a ticket.

89
00:08:27,714 --> 00:08:31,399
And it was all arranged to meet at the airport, you know, and he never turned up, you see.

90
00:08:32,539 --> 00:08:35,703
And it was just too much for this Australian guy.

91
00:08:36,443 --> 00:08:40,168
This was the absolute pits, a senior monk, you know.

92
00:08:40,187 --> 00:08:47,956
And I found that constantly in the East, the inability to say no and giving you the impression they're coming.

93
00:08:48,817 --> 00:08:49,437
And then they don't.

94
00:08:50,519 --> 00:08:52,861
Or they say they do something and then they don't.

95
00:08:53,482 --> 00:09:02,565
And I think it's to do with that Eastern thing about losing face and not being shamed, a shamed sort of culture rather than ours, which is more guilt-ridden.

96
00:09:03,793 --> 00:09:16,929
So I think that's an area where you see in the commentaries, it's only discussed, as far as I remember, to do with this keeping your word.

97
00:09:18,192 --> 00:09:27,363
So that gives you some ideas about this quality of satch of truthfulness, being absolutely honest.

98
00:09:28,043 --> 00:09:31,707
And I think the most difficult thing is to be honest with oneself, frankly.

99
00:09:32,110 --> 00:09:34,559
be brutally honest with oneself.

100
00:09:35,620 --> 00:09:37,322
to see oneself as one really is.

101
00:09:37,902 --> 00:09:39,884
And in a sense, that's the definition of humility.

102
00:09:40,224 --> 00:09:46,610
I mean, you know, in its proper sense, to see oneself as one really is.

103
00:09:47,490 --> 00:09:52,875
And you come across this way of talking about it in Buddhism.

104
00:09:53,936 --> 00:09:58,640
I don't know where this has come from, but when two people meet, there are six people there.

105
00:09:58,660 --> 00:10:03,585
There's me as I think I am, there's me as you think I am, and there's me as I really am.

106
00:10:04,225 --> 00:10:05,626
And the same applies to you.

107
00:10:05,606 --> 00:10:34,381
so how we communicate is a problem and it just shows how we have these self images which don't live up to the way other people see us and they see us from their vantage point they put a twist on us and seeing ourselves as we really are would cut through a lot of this any stuff that comes up through honesty

108
00:10:35,121 --> 00:10:36,604
So it's quite a virtue really.

109
00:10:38,566 --> 00:10:40,087
Quite a virtue to develop that.

110
00:10:42,530 --> 00:10:45,173
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

111
00:10:45,715 --> 00:10:57,990
May you be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

